F inally, it was planned to make a thorough study of the Latinity, so as to determine whether the language of the translation is the colloquial speech and whether elements are found therein that justify a conclusion as to the place of. its origin. It soon became apparent that the investigation as originally outlined would exceed the limits set upon this monograph, and it was finally decided to confine the present investigation to a reconstruction of the text, to a comparative study of the text with reference to its bearing upon the question of the unity both of St. Augustine's Bible and of the Old Latin Bible as a whole, and particularly to a study of the Latinity of the translation. It is hoped that the work as originally planned may be completed at a later date.
